---
// LLM101 page — embeds the interactive llm101 app at the top, then frames it
// with a Capability Matters editorial lens connecting LLM mechanics to
// practitioner capability development.
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import SectionHero from "../components/SectionHero.astro";

const LLM101_URL = "https://wrgr.github.io/llm101/";
---

<Base
  title="LLM101 · LENS"
  description="One mechanism. Five depths. An interactive guide to how large language models actually work — for everyone from curious beginners to ML practitioners."
  active="llm101"
>
  <SectionHero
    eyebrow="Interactive Learning"
    title="LLM101"
    claim="One mechanism. Five depths. An interactive guide to how large language models actually work — from a single metaphor to graduate-level formalism."
    question="How does next-token prediction become something that looks like intelligence?"
  />

  <section class="app-section">
    <div class="container-wide">
      <div class="embed-wrapper">
        <div class="embed-toolbar">
          <span class="embed-label">Interactive Explorer</span>
          <a
            href={LLM101_URL}
            class="embed-link"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            aria-label="Open LLM101 in a new tab"
          >
            <svg
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              width="13"
              height="13"
              fill="none"
              stroke="currentColor"
              stroke-width="2"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              stroke-linejoin="round"
              aria-hidden="true"
            >
              <path d="M18 13v6a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2V8a2 2 0 012-2h6"/>
              <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"/>
              <line x1="10" y1="14" x2="21" y2="3"/>
            </svg>
            Open full screen
          </a>
        </div>
        <div class="embed-frame">
          <iframe
            src={LLM101_URL}
            title="LLM101: How Large Language Models Actually Work"
            loading="lazy"
            allow="clipboard-write"
            scrolling="yes"
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="vignette-section">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="vignette-header">
        <p class="eyebrow">Capability Matters Lens</p>
        <h2>Why the mechanism matters to practitioners</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="vignette-body">
        <p class="lead">
          Understanding how large language models actually work is not a technical
          luxury — it is a capability prerequisite for anyone designing systems,
          teams, or learning environments that rely on them.
        </p>

        <p>
          LLM101 was built around a single observation: next-token prediction,
          repeated at enormous scale, generates behavior that looks remarkably
          like reasoning, comprehension, and creativity. Everything else — the
          architecture, the training, the alignment work — is infrastructure for
          making that prediction extraordinarily good. Practitioners who
          understand this are better positioned than those who don't, not because
          they need to implement a transformer, but because the mechanism shapes
          what these systems can and cannot reliably do.
        </p>

        <p>
          The five depth levels in LLM101 map onto different capability roles.
          A leader or commissioner needs "The Picture" — a reliable mental model
          sufficient to avoid the category errors that plague high-stakes
          deployment decisions. A practitioner working with LLMs daily benefits
          from the "Overview" view: enough mechanistic grounding to interpret
          surprising outputs and set realistic expectations with stakeholders.
          Engineers and curriculum designers need the "Under the Hood" view to
          make sound integration and evaluation choices. Only a small fraction of
          roles require the "Formal" level — and that fraction is not the whole
          capability ecosystem.
        </p>

        <p>
          What capability matters most here is calibration: knowing which depth
          you need, and being able to move between depths when the context
          demands it. LLM101 is designed to let you do exactly that — to dial
          from metaphor to mathematics and back again without losing the thread.
        </p>

        <h3>Questions this tool helps practitioners answer</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            When an LLM "hallucinates," what is actually happening — and who in
            your organization needs to understand it well enough to respond?
          </li>
          <li>
            What makes a prompt work? How does the prediction mechanism explain
            prompt sensitivity, context limits, and chain-of-thought behavior?
          </li>
          <li>
            Why does scale matter, and where are its limits? What should
            capability leaders expect from successive model generations?
          </li>
          <li>
            What does alignment mean technically — and how does that shape
            responsible deployment decisions?
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          These are not purely technical questions. They require a conceptual
          bridge between mechanism and organizational consequence. LLM101
          provides that bridge, at the depth appropriate to each role.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* ── App embed ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .app-section {
    padding: 2rem 0 0;
  }

  .embed-wrapper {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .embed-toolbar {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    padding: .45rem .9rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: var(--tint);
  }

  .embed-label {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: .72rem;
    letter-spacing: .1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .embed-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: .35rem;
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: .8rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    border: none;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
  .embed-link:hover {
    color: var(--accent-2);
    border: none;
  }

  .embed-frame {
    width: 100%;
    height: 740px;
    overflow: hidden;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;
    background: #fff;
  }

  .embed-frame iframe {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: none;
    display: block;
  }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .embed-frame { height: 620px; }
  }

  @media (max-width: 460px) {
    .embed-frame { height: 560px; }
  }

  /* ── Vignette ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .vignette-section {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    background: linear-gradient(to bottom, var(--tint) 0%, var(--bg) 5rem);
  }

  .vignette-header {
    margin-bottom: 1.75rem;
  }

  .vignette-header .eyebrow {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: .75rem;
  }

  .vignette-header h2 {
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 30rem;
  }

  .vignette-body .lead {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.05rem, 1.5vw, 1.18rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--ink);
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .vignette-body p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.68;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  .vignette-body h3 {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: .8rem;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .vignette-body ul {
    padding-left: 1.4rem;
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
  }

  .vignette-body li {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.62;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    margin-bottom: .6rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 560px) {
    .vignette-section { margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .vignette-body .lead { font-size: 1.02rem; }
  }
</style>
